<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Political figures, of any religion whatsoever, trying to make laws or policy decisions based on their beliefs is by definition unfair and oppressive to anyone else who happens to believe differently. It's just as wrong for christian political figures to make public policy based on Christian moral values as it would be for a Hindu politician outlawing the eating of Beef, a Jewish one outlawing Pork, or a Wiccan one demanding you call circle.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I would venture a guess that more than 90% of all of the criminal laws in the US are based on Christian moral ethics.  Many things that christians considered &quot;taboo&quot; were outlawed a very long time ago because the MAJORITY OF THE COUNTRY followed that belief system.  THE PEOPLE OF THE USA cried out for laws to prohibit what they felt was unacceptable in the society in which we live.  If 95% of the population follows christianity's moral code of ethics, then the politicians MUST create laws that will satisfy THAT GROUP.<br>
<br>
Politicians are chosen to act as representatives of the citizens of their county/city/state/country.  To mandate political doctrine based on a religious belief system is no more wrong than requiring people to be legally married before they can have tax deductions as such.  In case you hadn't noticed, marriage is a religious concept that became law.  Laws are designed to uphold the society for which they were written and there's no escaping this.<br>
<br>
I agree that it totally sucks, but that's how it works.  I'd have loved to have gone to the theatre and seen &quot;The Last Temptation of Christ&quot; but it was outlawed in this area.  You can't even buy it on video.<br>
<br>
