<br>
As an example, I think using many drugs SHOULD be legal, but driving a car while under the influence of them should be heinously ILlegal. In the first case, the only mind I'm bending or impacting is my own. In the second case, the instant I get behind the wheel, I threaten everyone else on the road's life and happiness. See the difference? <br>
<br>
Same thing with prostitution. Why is it illegal to sell something that it's perfectly legal to give away for free? Legislated Christian morality, that's why. If that's what an adult choses to do of their own free will, then why in hell shouldn't they be allowed to, subject of course to medical screening? Need to do the screening for the same reason why driving under the influence isn't allowed, ie, the safety of others. FORCING someone into prostitution however, would be UTTERLY illegal. <br>
<br>
You mention being an athiest disagreeing with abortion. While I am sure there ARE a few people like that, I don't think even you could claim that that's where MOST of the argument for banning it is coming from. 99% of the protest of abortion is coming from conservative christian groups. You know it, I know it, everyone knows it.<br>
<br>
Now, remember, I never said that you shouldn't be allowed to argue against it, nor should those christian organizations. That would be violating your rights of free speach. What you SHOULD NOT be allowed, however, is to make the decision for SOMEONE ELSE. It's their body, it's their life, it is their decision to make. Argue against it all you want, but the final decision MUST be left to the individual. The government CANNOT be the one to make that decision. You going to tell a 16 year old girl that was raped by her father and is now pregnant that she has to go through the emotional hell and deal with all of the life changes that carrying that baby to term will bring? What gives *YOU* the right to make that decision for HER?<br>
<br>
Having an opinion on a topic, and arguing your point is not forcing it down my throat, no. However, the government making LAWS that enforce that particular stance IS. See the difference? In the first case, you are exercizing your right to free speach, and attempting to convince me of the correctness of your point, but I am free to disregard your thoughts if I so chose, and I can turn around and tell you you're full of shit. The instance it becomes LAW however, I *MUST* abide by it, or risk loss of liberty and career, by being put in jail. In THAT case, the position has absolutely been forced upon me.<br>
<br>
You're right, Clinton did make steps for gays in the military, etc. And yes, he's a devout christian. Did you fail to see in my previous posts my saying I have NO ISSUE WHATSOEVER with someone who is a devout ANYTHING being president? My issue is ENTIRELY whether or not that individual tries to make the tenets of that religion PUBLIC policy, as opposed to PERSONAL policy. In this case, Clinton acted entirely properly by making domestic policy that was NOT based on his own personal religious beliefs. Applause for him.<br>
<br>
BTW, you still have yet to answer any of my earlier points...<br>
